# the plot shows that there is trend existed
# Autocorrelation function indicates that peaks appeared, which means that there is seasonality.
# Mean Forecast
#Predicts that all future values equal the historical mean of h02. The forecast line is flat because no trend or seasonality is modeled.
mean_forecast <- meanf(h02,5)
View(mean_forecast)
plot(mean_forecast)

mean_forecast

# Naive
# Assumes future = last observed value. Forecast line is horizontal starting at the last point of data.
naive_forecast <- naive(h02,5)
plot(naive_forecast)

# Random Walk
# The forecast line slopes upward because drift is positive.
rwf_forecast <- rwf(h02,5, drift=TRUE)
plot(rwf_forecast)

# Seasonal Naive
# Predicts each future period as the same value from the same season last year.
snaive_forecast <- snaive(h02,5)
plot(snaive_forecast)

# Moving Average
# Applies a 5-point or 9-point rolling average to smooth short-term noise of existing data.
# The MA(5) curve follows the data closely but smoother than the original.
# The MA(9) line is even smoother because it averages over a longer period.
MA5_forecast <- ma(h02,order=5)
plot(MA5_forecast)

MA9_forecast <- ma(h02,order=9)
plot(MA9_forecast)

# ETS
# Automatically captures level, trend, and possibly seasonality. The forecast plot shows a smooth continuation of recent trends and seasonal behavior.
ets_forecast <- ets(h02)
plot(ets_forecast)

ets_forecast2 <- forecast(ets_forecast,h=5)
plot(ets_forecast2)

# Holt-Winters
# Exponential smoothing model with smooths level, trend, and seasonality.
# The plot shows fitted in red line and actual values in black line. The forecasts continue both the trend and seasonal pattern.
HW_forecast <- HoltWinters(h02)
plot(HW_forecast)

HW_forecast2 <- forecast(HW_forecast,h=5)
plot(HW_forecast2)

# Simple Exponential Smoothing
# Only uses the level component without trend and seasonality. The plot shows the forecast is similar to the mean or naïve model, but slightly adjusted by alpha.
SSE_Simple <- ses(h02)
SSE_forecast <- forecast(SSE_Simple,h=5)
# Overlaying All Forecasts
# Red line (Naive) shows flat line at last value.
# Orange line (Random Walk) gently sloping up/down.
# Yellow line (Seasonal Naive) repeats seasonal cycles.
# Blue and Brown line (MA5 and MA9) show smoothed historical data.
# Pink line (ETS) show forecast with adaptive trend and seasonality.
# Green line (Holt-Winters) show forecast with trend and seasonal.
# Black line (SES) indicates smoothed flat forecast.
plot(mean_forecast)
lines(naive_forecast$mean,col="red")
lines(rwf_forecast$mean,col="orange")
lines(snaive_forecast$mean,col="yellow")
lines(MA5_forecast,col="blue")
lines(MA9_forecast,col="brown")
lines(ets_forecast2$mean,col="pink")
lines(HW_forecast2$mean,col="green")
lines(SSE_forecast$mean,col="black")
